  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. It involves the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, often through complex transactions, to make it appear as if it came from legitimate sources. This is considered a serious crime because it undermines the integrity of financial systems, facilitates other illegal activities, and has negative impacts on economic and social stability.\n\nIn China, money laundering is explicitly prohibited under relevant laws and regulations, including the Criminal Law and the Anti-Money Laundering Law. The Chinese government has established strict regulatory frameworks and enforcement mechanisms to combat money laundering, including financial institution reporting requirements, monitoring systems, and international cooperation. These efforts demonstrate China's firm commitment to maintaining social and economic order and upholding the rule of law.",
